uck and buy our full position at once. We will initiate a one-third position at the current market price. We will then set orders to add the next third if the stock pulls back another 10-15% on macro fears or general market weakness. The final third will be deployed either on a further significant dip or upon the next earnings report that confirms they are on track with their infrastructure build-out and revenue recognition from these key contracts. This approach embraces the volatility instead of fearing it.  2.  **Position Sizing: Calculated Risk.** Given the risk profile, this will not be one of our largest portfolio positions. It will be a meaningful allocation, reflecting our conviction, but sized appropriately so that a significant downturn won't cripple our overall performance. Think of it as a high-octane satellite position orbiting our core, more stable holdings.  3.  **Risk Management: Thesis-Based Stop-Loss.** Our stop-loss here is not a simple price percentage. A 20% drop in this stock could happen on a bad market week and would be a terrible reason to sell. Our exit strategy is tied to the thesis. We will monitor news related to Meta and Microsoft's AI spending like a hawk. Any credible news suggesting a material change, delay, or cancellation of their contracts with NBIS is our signal to exit the position immediately, regardless of the price. The contracts are the foundation of this investment; if that foundation cracks, we're out.  4.  **Time Horizon: 18-36 Months.** This is not a trade. This is an investment in a multi-year growth story. We need to give the company time to execute its massive capital expenditures and begin translating that $50 billion backlog into recognized revenue and, eventually, positive free cash flow. We will ignore the short-term social media chatter and focus on their quarterly progress reports against their long-term goals.  In short, we're buying a future leader validated by the biggest players in the game, at a moment when